---
import CaseStudyLayout from '../../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro';

const data = {
  metaTitle: "Sports Venue Ticketing & Membership System | All Webbed Labs Case Study",
  metaDescription: "How a Toowoomba football stadium moved from phone bookings to automated online ticketing, eliminating ticket fraud and growing sales by 38%.",

  industry: "Sports & Recreation",
  tags: ["Ticketing", "QR Scanning", "Season Passes", "Stripe", "Next.js"],

  title: "Sports Venue Ticketing & Membership System",
  summary: "A regional football stadium moved from phone bookings to a fully automated ticketing and season pass system, increasing sales by 38%.",

  heroImageDescription: "Gate staff scanning a QR code ticket on a mobile phone at a regional Queensland football stadium, crowd visible in background",

  // CASE_STUDY_PLACEHOLDER — replace with real client details when approved
  clientOverview: "A regional football stadium in Toowoomba, Queensland, with a seated and standing capacity of 4,200. The venue hosts 18 home games per season for the resident football club, and supplements revenue through concert bookings and community events. Owned and operated by a local trust that has managed the facility since the stadium's construction in 2008.",
  clientSize: "4,200 capacity · 18+ events/season",
  clientLocation: "Toowoomba, QLD",

  pullQuote: "We had people driving 40 minutes to buy a ticket at the gate only to find the section they wanted was already sold out. Now they can check availability on their phone and buy in under two minutes. The frustration for fans just dissolved, and our Saturday gate queues are a fraction of what they were.",
  pullQuoteAuthor: "Venue Operations Manager",
  pullQuoteRole: "Stadium Trust, Toowoomba",

  challenge: [
    "The stadium had no online ticket sales capability at all. Every ticket was either purchased at the gate on match day or through a phone booking process where staff took card details over the phone — a process that created data security obligations the trust was not equipped to manage properly, and that was only available during limited office hours. For fans travelling from regional areas, the lack of advance purchase confirmation was a genuine deterrent. For the venue, it meant that attendance data was a by-product of gate counts rather than a proper record of who was in the building.",
    "Season passes were issued as laminated paper cards with printed photographs and a sequential serial number. Renewing members would receive a new card by post each season. The system relied entirely on gate staff visually matching the photo to the cardholder — a process that was slow, inconsistent in application, and impossible to verify meaningfully during busy entry periods when gate queues stretched back to the car park. The trust had received reports of pass sharing, particularly for corporate hospitality areas where the passes had significant resale value.",
    "Ticket fraud had become a material financial issue. The trust estimated, based on gate count discrepancies and anecdotal evidence from stewards, that fraudulent entry was occurring at a rate of roughly 3–4% of total attendance — primarily through photocopied or photographed paper tickets being presented at gates where staff weren't checking closely. Over a full season across 18 home games, the accumulated loss was substantial. A post-season accounting review had confirmed that lost revenue from estimated fraudulent admissions exceeded $34,000 in the prior season.",
    "The venue had no mechanism to collect or use attendance data. They could count how many people entered, but not which tickets had been used in which zone, whether certain fixture types drove higher no-shows, or what the actual demand profile looked like for different seating categories. Decisions about pricing, concert bookings, and capital investment in facilities were made without meaningful data. The trust's board had started asking for numbers that the operations team simply couldn't produce from the systems they had."
  ],

  whyUs: [
    "The trust's operations manager had worked with a contact at another Queensland regional venue that had gone through a similar technology upgrade. That venue had worked with a national events ticketing platform and found the per-ticket fees eroded margins substantially at their scale, while the platform's configuration options didn't accommodate the mix of football, community events, and concerts the Toowoomba venue hosted. The contact recommended a custom-built solution as a better long-term investment, which led to an introduction to All Webbed Labs.",
    "We spent the initial scoping conversations being honest about where a custom build made economic sense versus where an off-the-shelf integration would serve them better. Stripe's payment infrastructure was the right answer for payment processing — there was no value in rebuilding that. The ticketing logic, the season pass management, the QR scanning workflow, and the management reporting layer were all genuinely custom requirements where a tailored solution would serve the trust better than a generic platform designed for stadium operators with ten times the venue capacity."
  ],

  approach: [
    "Discovery involved a site visit during a match day — the single most informative few hours of the project. We observed gate entry queues from opening until the end of half-time, watched how staff handled the paper ticket and season pass processes, and spoke with gate stewards about the pressure points during busy periods. The entry flow during a close match with a large crowd is very different from the dry-run scenario any lab test would simulate, and understanding the operational reality shaped almost every subsequent design decision.",
    "The key technical decision was the QR scanning architecture. We evaluated two approaches: a dedicated scanning device per gate using purpose-built hardware, and a mobile web app that allowed gate staff to use standard smartphones. The dedicated hardware approach offered faster scan processing but required significant capital expenditure and ongoing maintenance contracts. Given the venue's event frequency — busy on 18 football days but quiet for the other 40-odd weeks of the year — the smartphone approach was clearly more practical. We built a mobile-optimised scanning interface using the device camera API that processed a scan and returned a pass/fail result in under a second on a standard Android phone.",
    "Season pass migration was a careful process. The trust had approximately 680 season pass holders from the prior season, with records held across a combination of a payments spreadsheet and a physical filing system for the paper application forms. We designed a migration flow where existing pass holders received an email invitation to create an account and claim their digital pass, with the trust's staff able to manually verify and approve any claim that didn't match the records they held. This avoided a bulk import of potentially stale data while giving genuine holders a smooth path to the new system.",
    "The development timeline was fourteen weeks, with a hard deadline driven by the start of the pre-season ticket sales window. We scoped the project to hit that deadline with the core ticketing, season pass, and scanning functionality complete, with the full reporting dashboard and event management features targeted for delivery four weeks after go-live. This phased approach meant the first home game of the season ran on the new system without the complexity of a simultaneously launched management reporting layer."
  ],

  solution: [
    "The platform is built on Next.js for both the public-facing ticket purchase experience and the venue management dashboard, with a Node.js API layer and PostgreSQL database on Supabase. Supabase was chosen for its managed PostgreSQL offering, built-in real-time subscription support (useful for gate status dashboards), and row-level security features that simplified the permission model for different staff roles without requiring a complex custom authorisation layer.",
    "Stripe powers all payment processing. Each ticket purchase creates a Stripe PaymentIntent, and on successful payment, the platform generates a unique QR code using a signed token containing the ticket ID, event ID, and an HMAC signature. The QR code can only be validated by the scanning app, which verifies the signature server-side before returning a result — meaning photocopied or screenshot QR codes work exactly once and are invalidated on first scan. Season passes generate a persistent QR code linked to the pass record, with an automatic refresh cycle every 30 days to further reduce the viability of shared screenshots.",
    "The gate scanning interface is a mobile web app pinned to the home screen on venue-supplied Android phones. When a QR code is scanned, the app sends the token to the validation API and receives a colour-coded response: green for valid admission, amber for already-scanned (with the original scan timestamp and gate location), and red for invalid or expired. Staff see the result in under a second. The API maintains a per-event scan log that the operations manager can review in real time from the management dashboard — useful for monitoring gate throughput during large events and identifying if a gate is falling behind.",
    "The ticket purchase flow was designed to be usable without an account for single-event tickets — requiring registration adds friction that reduces conversion for casual purchasers. Season pass management, however, requires an account, which enables the trust to maintain accurate records of pass holders and manage renewals with tracked communication. The checkout flow was tested on a range of device types common in regional Queensland, with particular attention to older iOS devices that some patrons were still using. We also implemented Apple Pay and Google Pay in the checkout to reduce card entry abandonment.",
    "The management dashboard gives venue staff real-time visibility of sales by event, seating category, and sales channel (online, gate, or comp). Season pass renewals are managed through a dashboard workflow that lets staff send renewal invitations in batches, track confirmation rates, and identify lapsed holders who haven't renewed after two reminders. Post-event attendance reports export to CSV and are formatted to align with the trust's existing reporting obligations to its board and the club."
  ],

  techStack: [
    { name: "Next.js", reason: "Full-stack framework for both public ticketing site and management dashboard — fast page loads critical for checkout conversion" },
    { name: "Supabase", reason: "Managed PostgreSQL with built-in real-time subscriptions for gate status — reduced infrastructure overhead significantly" },
    { name: "Stripe", reason: "Card payments, Apple Pay, Google Pay — critical for checkout conversion on mobile devices" },
    { name: "QR Code Generation", reason: "HMAC-signed tokens for tamper-resistant, single-use ticket validation" },
    { name: "Node.js", reason: "API layer for ticket validation and business logic, deployed as serverless functions" },
    { name: "PostgreSQL", reason: "Relational schema for events, tickets, passes, scans, and users with complex multi-table queries" }
  ],

  implementation: [
    "Gate staff training took place across two sessions in the week before the first home game. The scanning app was designed to be operable with virtually no training — the colour-coded response system was specifically chosen because it works even when staff are under pressure, in bright sunlight, or managing a queue of impatient supporters. Both training sessions focused more on handling edge cases (lost phones, network outages, patrons presenting both physical and digital) than on the scanning workflow itself, which staff picked up in under five minutes.",
    "The pre-season ticket sale opened three weeks before the first game. The trust sent an email to their existing season pass database and promoted online sales through their social media channels. Within 48 hours, more than 800 accounts had been created and the first 400 season pass renewals had been confirmed. The volume of first-day sales exceeded what the trust had achieved in the entire previous off-season through phone bookings, and no card details were taken over the phone.",
    "The first match day revealed one unanticipated operational issue: a section of the venue had intermittent 4G coverage due to a nearby building obstruction. Gate scanning in that section was occasionally slow to return a validation result when network latency spiked. We addressed this within two weeks by implementing a local caching layer in the scanning app that stored validated scan results offline and synced to the server when connectivity restored — a change that also improved scanning speed across the entire venue by reducing round-trip API calls for tickets that had been pre-cached."
  ],

  lessonsLearned: [
    "The offline scanning fallback should have been in scope from the beginning. It was an obvious risk that we identified during discovery but deferred as a phase two item to hit the launch deadline. When it became an issue on the first match day — in a lower-stakes section of the ground, fortunately — it was a reminder that venue environments have connectivity unpredictability that office-based testing environments don't simulate. Any future ticketing or gate management project will have offline resilience in scope from day one.",
    "The trust had a more complex comp ticket management process than they initially described. Corporate sponsors, media accreditation, club officials, and officials' guests all needed different access pathways that had historically been managed through separate paper lists held by different staff members. Reconciling this into a single system mid-project required an additional two weeks of scope that wasn't in the original estimate. The lesson: comp ticket workflows are almost always more complex than clients initially communicate, and discovery questions need to probe this area specifically.",
    "Regional venue patrons include a meaningful proportion who are uncomfortable with digital purchases or don't have smartphones. We built the gate sale capability — cash and card purchases at the gate terminal — as a day-one requirement, but we could have done more to help the trust communicate the change to their most loyal patrons before the season started. A handful of long-standing season pass holders arrived on day one expecting to renew their paper pass in person and were confused by the new process. The trust handled it graciously, but a pre-season letter to prior season pass holders explaining the change would have prevented the friction."
  ],

  whatCameNext: [
    "Six months after launch, the trust used the attendance data they'd accumulated to make the first evidence-based pricing decision in the venue's history — moving corporate hospitality package pricing up by 18% based on demonstrated demand in that section, and introducing a lower-priced family zone in a section that had consistently tracked the lowest per-game utilisation. Both decisions were made with reference to the dashboard's attendance heat maps rather than intuition.",
    "The trust has since asked us to scope a concert and community event module that adapts the ticketing system for general admission events with different zone configurations, merchandise add-ons at checkout, and integration with their existing event catering supplier's ordering system. The modular architecture of the original build means this extension is straightforward rather than a rebuild."
  ],

  resultsNarrative: "The shift from a phone-and-gate operation to a fully digital ticketing system changed the economics of the venue's match day operations fundamentally. Fraud losses were eliminated in the first season. Online sales accounted for 81% of revenue within six months of launch. The attendance data collected over the first season gave the trust's board more evidence to work with than they'd had in the previous five years combined.",

  metrics: [
    { value: "38%", label: "Increase in ticket sales", context: "Across the first full season on the platform" },
    { value: "81%", label: "Of sales now online", context: "Up from 0% before the platform launched" },
    { value: "8s", label: "Average gate processing time", context: "Down from 45 seconds per person with paper tickets" },
    { value: "$34K", label: "Annual fraud losses eliminated", context: "Based on prior-season estimate from gate count discrepancies" },
    { value: "29%", label: "Increase in season pass renewals", context: "First renewal season on the digital platform" },
    { value: "2,100", label: "Registered accounts", context: "Created in the platform's first season" }
  ],

  relatedCaseStudies: [
    {
      title: "Rugby Club Management App",
      href: "/case-studies/rugby-club-management-app",
      industry: "Sports & Recreation",
      summary: "A NSW rugby union club replaced paper-based rosters and manual fee collection with a full member management platform — cutting admin time by 60%."
    },
    {
      title: "Restaurant Booking & Table Management System",
      href: "/case-studies/restaurant-booking-table-management",
      industry: "Hospitality",
      summary: "A four-venue Sydney restaurant group unified bookings, waitlists and POS across all sites — eliminating double-bookings and reducing no-shows by 31%."
    },
    {
      title: "Café Loyalty & Rewards App",
      href: "/case-studies/cafe-loyalty-rewards-app",
      industry: "Hospitality",
      summary: "A 12-location café franchise launched a branded loyalty app that drove a 27% increase in repeat visits within the first six months."
    }
  ],

  relatedServices: [
    { title: "Custom Software Development", href: "/services/custom-software-development" },
    { title: "Payment Integration", href: "/services/payment-integration" },
    { title: "Mobile App Development", href: "/services/mobile-app-development" },
    { title: "Data & Analytics", href: "/services/data-analytics" }
  ]
};
